body:
I found a case where `request.params` becomes undefined. Here is a concrete test case to reproduce the case:

```javascript
// test/app.router.js

it('should have req.params in finish event after handler2 calls next', function(done){
  var app = express();

  function handler1(req, res, next) {
    res.once('finish', function() {
      setTimeout(function() {
        assert(req.params.id);
      })
    })

    next()
  }

  function handler2(req, res, next){
    res.end(req.params.id);
    next()
  }

  app.get('/user/:id', handler1, handler2);

  request(app)
  .get('/user/1')
  .expect(200, '1', done);
})
```

The test runs fine if there is no `next` call in `handler2`. The `setTimeout` in `handler1` ensures that the test fails.

As I understand it, the last `next` will cause the function `done` to be called in the router:

```javascript
// lib/router/index.js

// no more matching layers
if (idx >= stack.length) {
    setImmediate(done, layerError);
    return;
}
```

The problem is that `done` is not working correctly in this case. If there are middlewares and no router the `done` function will replace `baseUrl`, `next`, and `params` with the value `undefined`.

```javascript
// lib/router/index.js

// restore vals
for (var i = 0; i < props.length; i++) {
    obj[props[i]] = vals[i];
}
```

Hence the `setTimeout` in the `handler1`. Without a timeout, the `handler1` function mostly finishes successfully before `done` is called in the next iteration of the event loop.

My proposal to fix the problem would be to check for `undefined`:

```javascript
// lib/router/index.js

// restore vals
for (var i = 0; i < props.length; i++) {
  if (vals[i] !== undefined) {
    obj[props[i]] = vals[i];
  }
}
```

Before creating a pull request I would like to hear if I missed some details or a better solution.

I think better would if the `done` function would not try to restore anything if there is no router at all. But I could not figure out a good way to do that.
